    		<p class="text-justify">
            	&nbsp &nbsp  Currently around 1.4 billion people in the world still have no access to power and 400
				million of them live in rural areas of India. In India per capita consumption in rural
				households is only 8 units per month as compared to 24 units in urban households. The 
				reason for such low level of consumption is not low demand, but poor and unreliable supply of electricity. Poor access to energy facilities in rural areas is a result of poor grid connectivity and lack of distribution network for renewable and clean energy technologies.               
            </p>   
            <p class="text-justify">
            	&nbsp &nbsp Conventional perception is that people in rural areas cannot afford progressive and modern energy technologies but our experience of working in rural areas has made us believe that most of them are willing to pay for a reliable source of energy provided the product and service is customized as per their need and cash flow. A simple and customised solar energy system can meet basic energy needs of a rural household and reduce the problem of energy poverty plaguing more than 40% of our country living in rural areas. Electricity is one of the basic necessities of life and lack of energy services impact upon all aspects of peopleâ€™s lives and livelihoods. The introduction of even a limited source of electrical power can have immediate and significant economic, health and communication benefits for the people suffering from energy poverty. This shows the scale of the problem under consideration and its underlying potential for an enterprise based model.
